# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ethernet-ip
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] The **Common Industrial Protocol** (**CIP**) is an industrial protocol for industrial automation applications.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] Previously known as Control and Information Protocol, CIP encompasses a comprehensive suite of messages and services for the collection of manufacturing automation applications – control, safety, synchronization, motion, configuration and information.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] It allows users to integrate these manufacturing applications with enterprise-level Ethernet networks and the Internet.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] It is supported by hundreds of vendors around the world, and is media-independent.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] CIP provides a unified communication architecture throughout the manufacturing enterprise.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] It is used in EtherNet/IP, DeviceNet, CompoNet and ControlNet.
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] ODVA is the organization that supports network technologies built on the Common Industrial Protocol (CIP).
[src:ethernet-ip/common-industrial-protocol] These also currently include application extensions to CIP: CIP Safety, CIP Motion and CIP Sync.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] EtherNet/IP uses Ethernet as its data link and physical layer, the Internet Protocol as its network layer, and TCP and UDP as its transport layer.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] EtherNet/IP performs at the session layer and above (layers 5, 6 and 7) of the OSI model.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] CIP uses its object-oriented design to provide EtherNet/IP with the services and device profiles needed for real-time control applications and to promote consistent implementation of automation functions across a diverse ecosystem of products.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] In addition, EtherNet/IP adapts key elements of the Internet Protocol suite to the CIP object model framework; for example, it uses UDP to transport I/O messages.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] Ethernet/IP was estimated to have about 30% share of the industrial Ethernet market in 2010 and 2018.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] Development of EtherNet/IP began in the 1990s within a technical working group of ControlNet International, Ltd.(CI), another trade and standards development organization.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] In 2000, ODVA and CI formed a joint technology agreement (JTA) for the development of EtherNet/IP.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] In 2009, the JTA was terminated and EtherNet/IP became under the sole control of ODVA and its members.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] Today, EtherNet/IP is one of four networks that adapt CIP to an industrial network along with DeviceNet, ControlNet and CompoNet.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] All of these networks are managed by ODVA, Inc.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] EtherNet/IP classifies Ethernet nodes into predefined device types with specific behaviors.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] A portable open-source implementation named OpENer was started in 2009.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] The source code is available on GitHub, under an adapted BSD license.
[src:ethernet-ip/ethernet-ip] An open-source C++ scanner library named EIPScanner is available on GitHub, under an MIT license.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:ethernet-ip/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet can also refer to the use of standard Ethernet protocols with rugged connectors and extended temperature switches in an industrial environment, for automation or process control.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Components used in plant process areas must be designed to work in harsh environments of temperature extremes, humidity, and vibration that exceed the ranges for information technology equipment intended for installation in controlled environments.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] The use of fiber-optic Ethernet variants reduces the problems of electrical noise and provides electrical isolation.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Some industrial networks emphasized deterministic delivery of transmitted data, whereas Ethernet used collision detection which made transport time for individual data packets difficult to estimate with increasing network traffic.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Typically, industrial uses of Ethernet employ full-duplex standards and other methods so that collisions do not unacceptably influence transmission times.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Industrial use requires consideration of the environment in which the equipment must operate.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Factory equipment must tolerate a wider range of temperature, vibration, physical contamination and electrical noise than equipment installed in dedicated information-technology wiring closets.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Since critical process control may rely on an Ethernet link, the economic cost of interruptions may be high and high availability is therefore an essential criterion.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet networks must interoperate with both current and legacy systems, and must provide predictable performance and maintainability.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] In addition to physical compatibility and low-level transport protocols, a practical industrial Ethernet system must also provide interoperability of higher levels of the OSI model.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] An industrial network must provide security both from intrusions from outside the plant, and inadvertent or unauthorized use within the plant.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] When an industrial network must connect to an office network or external networks, a firewall system can be inserted to control exchange of data between the networks.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] This network separation preserves the performance and reliability of the industrial network.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) communicate using one of several possible open or proprietary protocols, such as EtherNet/IP, EtherCAT, Modbus, Sinec H1, Profibus, CANopen, DeviceNet or FOUNDATION Fieldbus.
[src:ethernet-ip/industrial-ethernet] The idea to use standard Ethernet makes these systems more interoperable.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] ODVA technologies include the Common Industrial Protocol or "CIP" - ODVA's media-independent, object-oriented protocol - along with ODVA's network adaptations of CIP - EtherNet/IP, DeviceNet, ControlNet, and CompoNet.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] ODVA has more than 15 technical working groups, overseen by its Technical Review Board, which develop and enhance ODVA's implementation specifications for its technologies.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] These specifications define how a product shall be designed in accordance with the specifications.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] ODVA maintains a conformance testing practice to validate that products designed using ODVA technologies comply with the specifications and interoperate in multivendor systems.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] ODVA also provides other services to its members to promote the adoption of ODVA technologies by industry.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] ODVA is a US 501(c)6 corporation incorporated in the state of Wisconsin.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] Its headquarters are in Ann Arbor, Michigan U.S.
[src:ethernet-ip/odva-company] It also has conformance test service providers in North America, China, Germany, and Japan.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The semaphore feature of acquiring in one thread and releasing in another thread is not needed.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard() statement instead of a lock() and unlock() pair is C++ RAII.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard destructor ensures lock release in case of an exception.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] This solution can handle multiple consumer threads and/or multiple producer threads.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:ethernet-ip/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
